1. cs.GT (Game Theory): The paper proposes an online mechanism for incentivizing passengers to truthfully report their demand in ridesharing, which involves designing a mechanism that satisfies desirable properties such as ex-post incentive compatibility, individual rationality, and budget-balance. This is a classic problem in game theory, and hence, cs.GT is the most likely sub-category. 
2. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The paper deals with Autonomous Mobility-on-Demand (AMoD) systems, which are a type of intelligent transportation systems that use AI algorithms to optimize the routing and scheduling of vehicles. The proposed mechanism also involves using AI techniques to match passengers with vehicles. Hence, cs.AI is also a likely sub-category. 
3. cs.LG (Machine Learning): The paper involves designing a mechanism that uses machine learning algorithms to predict the demand for ridesharing services and match passengers with vehicles. Hence, cs.LG is also a likely sub-category. 
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper deals with designing a system for ridesharing in AMoD systems, which involves controlling the routing and scheduling of vehicles. Hence, cs.SY is also a possible sub-category.
